segments.text: Tell me your full name.
Tell me when you were born, where you were born, what you did as a young man, what you were interested in.
Tell me a little bit about your folks, what kind of influence they had on you, stuff like that.
Today is the 31st of July, 1997.
We're in San Antonio, Texas.
Good.
So if you could just begin.
With that, I appreciate it.
I'll interrupt you from time to time with questions or clarifications.
My name is Frank Adair Camp.
Would you spell Adair?
Adair is A-D-A-I-R, which was my mother's maiden name.
I was born December the 21st of 1920 in a very small town up in north central Texas named Blum, B-L-U-M.
My mother and father were ranchers right at the edge of town up on High Rocky Hill.
What's Blum near?
Blum is near the county seat of, it's in Hill County and the county seat is Hillsboro.
It's closer to Cleburne actually than it is to Hillsboro.
And a lot of people now can locate it because it's also on the edge of Lake Whitney.
Uh-huh.
And so people come there from Dallas and Fort Worth for fishing.
My mother died when I was four years old.
Suddenly, she'd had mastoiditis and she got pneumonia and died on December 24th, buried on Christmas Day.
My father never remarried.
He had one old mate's sister who came a couple of times in my growing up and lived with us.
And other cousins came.
The purpose of her coming primarily was because she lived out in the country where there was only a country school.
And these other two cousins had gone as far as they could go there and they needed to come into town.
and have a better school so she came to live with us.
But in the summer times I was living with grandparents mostly.
Where did your grandparents live?
They lived in the same area of Blum out in the country there.
My father's folks actually lived in a sandy land area there near Blanton really.
which was another just a wide place in the road.
My mother's people had a ranch right on the upper edges of the river that later became Lake Whitney.
Unfortunately, when my mother died, I went to live with her parents, and in April after my mother died, my grandmother died.
So, my mother had one brother who had been in the Navy in World War I.
He came home at the end of the war and decided to help his father with the ranch there.
He never married, but I was always relatively close to him.
and his father, and they lived out there on the ranch by themselves.
And I spent some time with them in the summer times.
Blum is a very small town.
There was only about 200 people in the town.
There were as many people in the school as there was in the town because it had a bus system that drew from around that whole area there.
although my graduating class from high school had a total of 14 of them, seven boys and seven girls.
And people have asked me sometimes, how come that you went to A&M?
Well, at that time, this was back, I graduated in 1938, right in the heart of the Depression.
People had very little money, very few people went to college.
I had a small,

inheritance from my mother that I used and why I chose A&M I really don't know except that I remember one time when I was about a sophomore or junior in high school that there was some evening occasion going on and there was a visit at this party so to speak
of some seniors from A&M.
And I was just intrigued by them.
So I wrote and got a catalog and decided that's where I'd like to go.
The thing that made it most inviting was that you could go there so cheaply because you were wearing uniforms which were partly furnished.
The most that I paid, for example, for a room and board my freshman year
was $27 a month.
The amount that they charged the board was based on their actual dining hall expenses the month before.
And so I could attend there and not have to
too much expense.
So did you enter A&M in 38?
I entered A&M in 38.
So you were a class of 42.
And of course in December 41 was when the Pearl Harbor plane came.
I went home at Christmas time and In 41?
In 41 and went to see my draft board.
Because A&M at that time had a

requirement that you had to stay at school my memory says April 15th it may have been May 1st if you were there that long they would give you your degree and so I went to the draft board and asked them if I would be able to stay there and they laughed at me and said you're crazy you're number 8 in the county and you'll be gone the first month and so I believed them
Actually, I didn't get drafted until the first week of July, as it turned out.
So you didn't go back to school then?
You stayed at home?
I stayed at school, but I didn't register for the second semester.
Oh.
But the government was paying for some special courses on campus.
And so even though I didn't want to lose my money, I didn't mind letting the government pay for something for me.
And I could stay on campus with my friends and this sort of thing until I got called.
So July of 41, you got drafted?
July of 41.
42, I got drafted.
That's right.
And I was working.
One of the courses that I took at this A&M thing was a course called Testing and Inspection of Engineering Materials.
They still teach that.
Of which I had absolutely no background for.
I know nothing, just a friend who approved me so I could get in it.
But anyway, when I got through it, an Aggie who had a big construction company up in Dallas
was hiring all of us to help build army camps.
So I went from A&M, when I finished that course, up to Gainesville, north of Fort Worth and Dallas, up there near the Oklahoma border, and helped them build an army camp.
And on the weekend of 4th of July, I came home and found my draft notice there.
And so I went in the next morning
to Dallas and went to the Naval recruiting office and they asked me, what do you want to do in the Navy?
I said, I just want in the Navy.
Now, why did you choose the Navy?
Was that because of this uncle?
This uncle of yours?
This uncle of mine, he had a very interesting experience during World War I, loved the Navy and
So I had listened to him in my childhood, and just decided that's what I wanted to do.
I didn't want to go in the Army, because I'd heard all kinds of tales about Army life, too.
So I went into the recruiting office, told them I wanted to join the Navy, and they wanted to know what I wanted to do.
And I said, I just want to join the Navy.
But they noticed that I was working on a construction camp, so they said, we'll put you in the Seabees.
That's construction battalions.
Well, actually, I knew nothing about construction.
But anyway, I was sent.
That never stopped the military.
No, it never stopped them.
I rode from Dallas to Norfolk, Virginia on a train, open air.
When I say that, all the windows were open.
We all looked like black people when we got there because of the smoke.
The soot.
The soot coming in.
Got in on a Wednesday.
checked in to the base, and they very quickly made assignments for the rest of the week.
And I got assigned to the gate duty on Sunday, which I was not very happy about, because that was the one day we had a little off and a little freedom.
Actually, it turned out to be very lucky in that during the morning, the officer that was in charge
detail, asked if anyone could type.
Well, I was the only one that could.
Those other construction people, they could hardly do anything besides doing their job.
Anyway, after I helped him with his reports and everything, later on in the day, he said, Camp, I just got a notice down that they want people to come up in the morning
me to send some people up to strike for yeoman and he said I don't know anything about a yeoman except I know he types and said you can type, you're heading my detail to go up there.
So I went up there and was interviewed by a petty officer, chief petty officer.
He kept asking me questions and finally he said you're
really overqualified for the job that I had.
He said, I just was looking for somebody to kind of be a messenger for the time being.
And he said, I'm going to send you over for another interview.
So he sent me over to another building.
And I ended up being interviewed by the executive officer of the base.
And he talked to me for a little while.
And he said, where are you now?
And I said, well, I'm in boot camp.
And he said, well, as of in the morning, you're in my office.
So he said, You didn't have to go to boot?
I did not go to boot.
I can't believe this.
That's what people do.
And I went to work for him, and we had a very good relationship.
One day he called me, and he said, Why haven't you applied for midshipman school?
I said, You've got all the qualifications for officer training.
And I said, Well, I just haven't.
I said, I'm happy with doing what I'm doing.
I'm doing my job.
He said, nah.
He said, I want your application on my desk this week.
So I went over, got my physical, and turned it in to him.
And thinking, because I'd been actually helping with those applications, it takes about six months before anything happens.
So I thought, by that time, I'll probably be ready for a change.
So he took it to Washington.
I had orders for the month it was over.
And I went to Ben Shipman School in Chicago.
Oh, the Naval Station.
No.
Downtown Chicago at the medical school, which they had taken over part of those buildings.
And it was right next to a big armory.
It would have been an army.
Or were they trained there for, I guess, like the guard or something like that.
They had that, and they took over where I lived, had been a woman's athletic club, high-rise athletic club.
And then they had the dormitories also that medical students had lived in.
So they took over that facility.
Well, the nice thing about it was that we were the only officer-type military in the downtown Chicago area.

So when I checked in on Sunday, when I arrived there, after I'd completed all their forms and got my room assignment and all this, they said, there's a lady out at the table on the veranda out there that would like to talk to you right there.
Well, this was the social director of the Chicago Yacht Club.
And she was inviting all of us, the incoming class, to come to a tea that afternoon to meet her girls.
She had all these debutantes that were parents who were members of the Chicago Yacht Club there.
And in order to have nice escorts for them, she depended on the midshipman school people.
So we did that.
We all met.

nice young ladies who were looking for a good time and whose father had plenty of money to help us have a good time and on Saturday morning we had a review and when that was over we were free for the weekend.
The girl that I got to know whose father was a professor out at Northwestern furnished me a car, furnished me money,
to entertain his daughter.
So the war was a trial.
The war was a trial.
It really was.
I graduated from there at Christmas time.
This was in 42 then?
No, this was in 43, I believe.
So you were there...
I went there... Actually, it took a little bit longer for me before I left for going there.
I was...
I was a yeoman first in Norfolk, and then after a few months they moved us up to Williamsburg, Virginia.
And I was up there for several months before I actually went in.
I'd been there probably six months or so before.
So it was, I went to midshipman school in September of 43 and graduated in December.
Oh, so it was three or four months.
Well, I thought my luck had run out because 90,
7% of our midshipmen class were assigned to a small craft in the Navy with the great majority of those being sent to the Pacific area.
But I lucked out again.
I got an assignment.
I was in the LCTs, which is landing craft tanks, which is a small thing.
It can carry three tanks on its deck, and it's kind of like a floating bathtub.
But I went to New Orleans to pick it up and to get my crew and they put me on top of a larger landing craft called an LSD.
We got outfitted, went back to Norfolk, picked up some stuff there and then started our 30 day crossing of the Atlantic.
Supposedly to go to Italy to do some work on the
beachheads there in Italy.
Now you were incident at this point?
Incident at this point.
What was your duty aboard the LST?
Well, I wasn't supposed to have any duty aboard the LST but the captain of the LST made you do everything he wanted you to do.
He stood all the watches and did everything just like a regular officer did.
Anyway, we got to North Africa.
They launched us off, put the
That's LST at a list, and they had us on a special box.
They knocked those blocks out, and we slid off into the water.
And I was supposed to leave the next morning for the Anzio beachhead to relieve some ships that were taking a beating up there.
About 10 o'clock that night, officers came aboard and said, Camp, you have new orders.
we're sending you to England.
We're gonna tow you back to Algiers, which has a crane big enough to lift you back on the LSD.
And then, so I took another 30-day little thing, because they just go way out into the Atlantic and back to Mississippi.
The dangers.
Incidentally, on the way over,
Just as we passed, or if we were nearing Gibraltar, we were attacked by JU-88s.
And we ended up, because I had a captain on that LST that was a pretty smart old guy.
And he got away from all the other ships and was out by himself, so to speak.
And we brought a JU-88 down.
He kind of grazed our deck and that.
brought him down, and we got a silver star.
That's really the most dangerous part of the war for me.
And then when we got to England, we landed in Ireland, because we had to go to another place that had a crane big enough to lift me off again.
So I got off actually in Cardiff, Wales, right across from Ireland, and then sailed around
the base, by the time we got there, they had all of the assignments already made for D-Day.
So they had us in reserve.
And I got an assignment that could not be, I could not land on the beach until it was secured.
So I didn't go in until D plus six.
And I had three tanks that I took in.
Then after I took those tanks in on D plus six, my assignment was to unload ammunition.
And I would go alongside of these ships and they would put 100 tons of ammunition on my deck.
And then when the tide.
So your LCT was like a lighter going back and forth.
We had those big tides on that beach there.
We'd go in on the beach at high tide and anchor.
The tide would go out and then we'd drop our bow down and they'd just come on there with trucks and take everything off.
Well that was all right until, of course the first night or two it wasn't very nice because you had aircraft coming over and attacking the beach every night.
But if you ever got hit,
You didn't have to worry because that was the end.
Anyway, in July, first part of July, we had a terrible storm on the beach.
And if the Germans had really known how bad off we were, they could have wiped us out because we got down to the fact that there was less after that storm.
all got tore up there.
Mulberries were all busted up.
Oh, everything was busted up.
They had at one time less than 12 hours of gasoline that they could deliver.
They had to beach ships that had gasoline, these five gallon things of gasoline on them.
They'd beach those and take it off that way.
And so I worked on that beach until that storm, but I had gotten pretty badly torn up, so they towed me back to England and put me in repair.
I stayed there for, I guess, about six weeks, and then went back to the beach.
But I wasn't on the beach for about less than one month until somebody came on board and said,
Well, you've got a new assignment.
I said, I do.
He said, yes, you're the new flotilla officer for the group.
He said, you're going back to England.
So I went back to England and lived in a nice home that we had for our headquarters.
Where was this?
It was in Salkham.
It's in southern England, close to Plymouth.
Oh, OK. And we had a beautiful headquarters there.
And so we stayed there until the war was over.
When the war in Europe was over, my commanding officer asked four of us that had been on his staff if we would like to go back with him and be on a new staff, probably in the Pacific.
And we said yes, we'd like to.
So we all went back to Norfolk.
and went out to a little base called Camp Bradford.
Now, did you fly back or did you take a ship back?
Oh, we took a ship back.
The old George Washington.
Oh, the old liner, yeah.
Yeah.
Worst ride in the world.
Not only that, but it had been a hospital ship, and the beds were just metal things with a little pad on it, so it was like sleeping.
We came home that way.

When we got to New York, when the ship got to New York, when we got out of the narrows, they came aboard to give us assignments because we would have to stay in New York for a week or so until they decided where they were going to send us and this sort of thing.
So the four of us were standing on the deck.
This wave came up and said, where would you all like to stay in New York?
What hotel?
And thinking that we were being a little smart ass, we said, the Hilton.
Well, it was the Waldorf then.
And she said, OK.
So she gave us a suite at the Waldorf.
Of course, the Warduff was not like it is today.
It wasn't air conditioned.
It had ceiling fans.
But it was nice.
It was beautiful.
And I laugh and say that the quality of the Warduff was really shown when I left there to go home.
I threw an old pair of shoes they were practically had holes in the bottom of them in the trash can.
When I got home, they had mailed them home to me.
Of course, leather was then very hard to get.
They thought that I shouldn't throw them away, I guess.
Anyway, we were stationed there in Camp Bradford waiting on an assignment and had nothing to do.
So the four of us played bridge from 8 o'clock in the morning to 5 o'clock in the afternoon when we could leave the base.
Then the war in Japan was over.
We still hadn't been assigned out there.
So what they were doing, we were all four of us were single.
And they- Now you'd been promoted though.
You were- Oh yeah, I was- You were a lieutenant probably or- I was either a JG or a lieutenant.
I can't remember which.
I think I was just a JG.
We all got assignments to going out to the Pacific, except that they all went out to ships in the Pacific to relieve officers who had enough points to come home.
And so they would bring the ship back, you see.
Where did I go?
I went to Long Beach, California.
I became what was called a passenger transportation officer.
In other words, I was arranging troop trains for people who, as they'd get to the States, to go back to bases for separation.
And so that was my assignment for four years.
Actually, ships quit coming in to the Los Angeles harbor.
San Pedro.
Yeah, San Pedro there.
And we were getting almost nothing.
So I'd go to the office and check my dispatches and take care of what little there was, and I was free the rest of the day.
Now, about this time, you must have made a decision that maybe you wanted to stay in the Navy a little longer.
Well, lots of people were doing this and were staying, but I was looking at it that, hell, that in a few months there wouldn't be any Navy like we have now.
Right.
And that the people from out of...
Annapolis would get all the plum officer assignments.
I didn't think there was much future in the Navy.
So I planned immediately to come back to A&M and go to school and finish my degree.
So although I could have gotten out in about April, I stayed until August.
Stay on Navy pay.
This is August of 46.
Yeah.
And then I came home and started school in September.
And stayed, actually, I finished up my degree and started my master's there.
And jobs, though, were just absolutely impossible to get almost at that time.
I went out in West Texas to Breckenridge to visit a cousin of mine who had lived with us when I was a child.
We were almost like brothers and sisters rather than cousins.
And she had been a home economics teacher out there for quite a long time.
And I went out there during actually my spring break, I think.
At lunchtime, the superintendent came over and sat down at the table and got to talking, and he wanted to know what I was doing.
And I told him, I said, well, I'm finishing up some work down at A&M, and I don't know what I'm going to do.
I'm looking for a job.
He said, come in and talk to me.
So I went in and talked to him, and he offered me a job teaching in an elementary school.
So I went out there.
taught for two years and then became principal of this elementary school and stayed there another two years.
Well, there wasn't any Navy anywhere close.
So I hadn't really done anything.
You weren't separated.
We were just released to inactive duty is what we were doing.
Out of a clear blue sky, about Christmas time of 50, I got a
a letter from the Commandant of the 8th Naval District.
And he said, we're inviting all officers in the district who have had prior personnel experience to come in for a two-week conference to work on a special project.
Would you be interested in doing that?
If so, let us know.
So I wrote him back and said, yes, I'd be glad to have some Navy pay as compared to teaching

pay and Lynn and I were planning to get married that year in March and this conference was going to be about the same time so we decided well hey we'll send our wedding and get married and then go to New Orleans for the conference and I'll attend that in the daytime and we can then have fun well it that was what we did and
It turned out that they kept wanting me to come back down there because we wrote the manual that set up mobilization stations in case there was a general mobilization.
As a result of it, we were also in a special status so that they couldn't draft us, and that's why I missed the Korean War.
We, they wanted us to come back and revise the manual and this sort of thing every year.
I'd been doing this for several years and realized that I had about 10 or 11 years that were good quality years as far as qualifying for retirement was concerned.
And I thought, maybe I better get serious about this.
So I talked to them down there and they said, why don't you let us put you in a pay status in San Antonio?
So they assigned me to a unit here, and I'd go down for about two weeks.

I went weekly drill, you know, and everything, and then take two weeks every summer, which I would do in New Orleans, until the Navy got a little picky because I wasn't going to sea, getting any sea duty.
So I reached the point where I had to go to sea every other year, and I'd go to New Orleans every other year.
But it became, I developed a lot of good friends.
What would you do in your sea duty every other year?
I mean, was that two weeks again?
Yes, two weeks.
You'd go to sea.
I went one year on an aircraft carrier out of San Diego.
I most often went on a tin can or destroyer out of New Orleans.
And one year I went.
So this wasn't a two-week cruise, was it?
Yeah.
Oh, they just go out two weeks and then come back?
Yeah, it was a training cruise, strictly.
Oh.
Is this all reserve officers?
All reserve people, officers and enlisted.
They'd be both on board.
Usually they'd have these training ships that would do this, and so half of the crew would be regular and half of it would be reserve.
The captain was a regular Navy officer?
Oh, yeah.
Was his XO a regular Navy officer?
Oh, yeah.
All the top brass were regular Navy officers.
Sometimes you'd have assignments working with them, but it was strictly an observation type thing.
For instance, we went on that carrier out of San Diego, and that was training pilots who had not been, had duty landing on board a carrier.
So we worked 24 hours a day.
It was night and day.
You were only on duty half the time.
But it was a very interesting experience.
When did you do that in San Diego?
Was that in the late 50s, early 60s?
Probably the late 50s or early 60s, something like that.
That would have been interesting.
Yeah.
I went to Charleston, South Carolina one time.
But all the assignments were interesting.
Like one time, I went out of New Orleans and I had been late getting on board, so I got the worst officer quarters, the last one left, which was right up in the bow.
And before we got out of the river, we got a radio message to prepare for heavy seas when you hit the Gulf.
Well, I mean, that was the most miserable night of my Navy career, I think.
The seas were so heavy.
I was up in that bow and it was going like this and like this at the same time.
I couldn't stay in that bunk.
I finally moved up to the lounge and just slept on the couch up there.
Well, we went like to one time to Cuba, one time to Mobile, and all around that area.
Usually we were a part of some special training assignment where we had duties on board that ship and some exercise.
They had all kinds of training exercises they would do in the summertime in order to get training to reserve.
So I enjoyed every minute of it.
And finally, I got to the point where I was up to a full commander.
And there were very few of us assignments in the reserve center here that would allow officers in that rank to be in those assignments.
And I was a hold of the position and a lot of younger officers couldn't get promoted because of that.
And so I finally, after I had about 24 years of active duty time, it was counting for retirement, I just went ahead and retired and let some of those younger officers.
If I'd stayed one more year,
Hindsight's always better than foresight.
I would have probably made one more promotion, which was a biggie.
Yeah, the captain.
Yeah.
But I didn't.
And at the time, I didn't think that he was so important.
But I didn't realize that pay promotions were going to continue to go up and up.
And so my reserve retirement has become more and more important as I've gotten
older, especially in San Antonio that is such a military town, but we've got such excellent medical facilities as well as the commissary and all this PX and all this sort of thing.
So I really look back with a lot of pride on the days that I was in the
Yeah, I can understand that.
Now, did you continue to teach?
No, after we got married the next summer.
Because even at, I was an unmarried principal.
I was getting credit for four years of military, active military service.
And I was still, my take-home pay was less than $300 a month.
And so when we got married, and I was 30 years old by that time, and we wanted to have some family.
We knew we weren't going to be able to fool around too many years.
So the first summer after we got married in March, we went to Houston looking for a job.
And I had a cousin who got me to apply with General Mills for a job.
It was a good interview and everything, but they had no openings at the time.
So I got back to school and got started in about the middle of September.
They called me and said, we've got an opening in San Antonio.
Would you be interested in going to San Antonio?
And I said, well, I don't know.
I've never been to San Antonio, but been through it once, but that's all.
I said, I've just started
A school year?
Well, why don't you come down and look at it?
Well, I came down here and they made me an offer of a job here.
And I went back then, went into the superintendent's office and told him what had happened.
And he said, you know that I can't pay you that kind of money.
And he said, I don't think you should turn it down.
He said, I'll find somebody to take your place.
He said, go on and accept it.
So we came down here sometime in October and went to work for General Mills.
Well, it turned out that it was a bad choice only because that all the, my territory ran all the way from San Antonio out to Sanderson.
And up through the hill country.
In the city of San Antonio itself, I had nothing.
So you were on the road all the time.
All the road.
So I was on the road at least three weeks out of four.
And the first year that you're married, that was not very happening.
Well, in December, I fell on an icy sidewalk and broke a leg.
And it was the kind of break that they couldn't put a cast on.
We were living in a second floor apartment.
It didn't even have a shower in it.
It had a tub in it.
Well, that was the most miserable six weeks I had.
But I spent them reading one ads and everything.
And so by the time that my six weeks was up, I had accepted another job.
But I continued in the Navy.
So you stayed in the San Antonio area.
I stayed in the San Antonio area.
That was so you could keep the reserve.
Well, it was.
And the other thing was that when I'd been out in West Texas, I'd had lots of problems with silence trouble.
And I had almost nothing here in San Antonio.
Oh, indeed.
So I was very anxious to stay here.
And so we stayed here all these years as a result of that.

The first house that we lived in here, we stayed in it 35 years, simply because after my wife decided to teach, she's one of these people who is not a morning person, and she liked being five minutes from school.
And so we didn't move for a long time.
About the time that I retired from, I worked the last 25 years
before I retired was with Mutual of New York.
And after I retired from them, I built this house, which was the first thing, my first project.
And then I did some substitute teaching at Hersk High School for a few years, and then I got tired of that.
Now I'm to the point of where I just try to have enough money
to do as much traveling as possible.
That's good.
Where have you been traveling?
Well, if you look at that map up there, you'll see we've pretty well, we've been to South America twice.
We've been to Europe probably six or seven times.
Oh, the buttons are places you've been?
Yeah.
Oh, you've done a good job then.
We've been to Australia and New Zealand.
We've been down to Singapore and to Hong Kong and Manila and Java.
in that area.
We haven't done much as far as Africa is concerned.
We haven't been.

Lynn went over one year and kind of went into one little place in Africa, but that's about the extent of it outside of the two places that I got into when I was there in that short period of time in the war.
We're going back in October this year
We're flying to Paris, gonna be there for a week, and then we're gonna take a train over into Munich, because Germany is the cheaper place to rent a car in Europe.
And we'll pick up a car there.
Our favorite place in Europe is a little village up on the side of the mountain above Innsbruck called Muters.
And we're going to spend a couple of days there.
